On Feb 27, 2004, at 5:12 PM, Richard Atwell wrote:

> No, timing and rpm are related. If you advance the timing you'll find 
> that the engine speeds up. Retard the timing, the engine slows a 
> little and it pulls less vacuum: the piston is moving slower and has 
> more time to draw into the attempted volume of air.

Aha, I see... if it draws the air more slowly, the restriction at the 
throttle body has less of an effect, thereby reducing the difference.

Got it, thanks Richard :-)

